## Cache Types

### 1. Rails.cache (Low-Level Caching)

Store any serializable data with a key.

```ruby
# Write to cache
Rails.cache.write('articles_count', Article.count, expires_in: 1.hour)

# Read from cache
count = Rails.cache.read('articles_count')

# Fetch (read or write)
count = Rails.cache.fetch('articles_count', expires_in: 1.hour) do
  Article.count
end

# Delete from cache
Rails.cache.delete('articles_count')

# Check if key exists
Rails.cache.exist?('articles_count')

# Clear entire cache (use sparingly!)
Rails.cache.clear
```

### 2. Fragment Caching (View Caching)

Cache portions of rendered HTML.

```erb
<!-- app/views/articles/index.html.erb -->

<h1>Articles</h1>

<% cache ['articles-list', Article.maximum(:updated_at)] do %>
  <div id="articles-list-container">
    <%= render @articles %>
  </div>
<% end %>
```

### 3. Russian Doll Caching (Nested Fragments)

Cache nested partials with automatic invalidation.

```erb
<!-- app/views/articles/_article.html.erb -->

<% cache article do %>
  <article id="<%= "article-#{article.id}-card" %>" class="bg-white rounded-lg shadow-md p-6 mb-4">
    <h2><%= article.title %></h2>
    <p><%= article.body.truncate(200) %></p>
    
    <!-- Nested cache for comments -->
    <% cache ['article-comments', article, article.comments.maximum(:updated_at)] do %>
      <div id="article-<%= article.id %>-comments">
        <%= render article.comments %>
      </div>
    <% end %>
  </article>
<% end %>
```

### 4. Collection Caching

Optimize caching for collections.

```erb
<!-- Cache each article individually -->
<%= render partial: 'articles/article', collection: @articles, cached: true %>

<!-- With custom cache key -->
<%= render partial: 'articles/article', 
           collection: @articles, 
           cached: ->(article) { [article, 'v2'] } %>
```

